{
  "doc_id": "55797",
  "text": "Although relatively few invertebrate cellulase systems have been fully characterised, it appears that other systems share the ability to digest cellulose without a cellobiohydrolase. Cellobiohydrolases appear to play no role in the initial digestion of cellulose by termites and wood-eating cockroaches [CITATION_1] ; cellulolytic systems from these insects consist of multiple endo--1,4-glucanases and -glucosidases [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Other invertebrate endo--1,4-glucanases are known to produce cellobiose, cellotriose and cellotetraose [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] , whereas partially purified -glucosidases from other species are able to hydrolyse cellotriose, cellotetraose and cellopentaose [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . It is possible that the cellulase system from these animals employs a similar mechanism to that of G. natalis. In addition to insects, cellulose hydrolysis in the mollusc Corbicula japonica occurs as a result of an endo--1,4-glucanase, with some activity towards crystalline cellulose, and a -glucosidase [CITATION_12] . This further strengthens the argument that cellobiohydrolases are absent from a broad range of invertebrate animal phyla.",
